[2] Diarrhea - India (Punjab)
Date: Sun 3 Jul 2011
Source: Times of India [edited]
http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Diarrohea-outbreak-in-Ropar-46-cases/articleshow/9082297.cms


Five people, including 2 foreigners, were admitted in Ropar Civil
Hospital on Saturday [2 Jul 2011] in what is turning out to be a
diarrhea outbreak in the city. In all, 46 cases of diarrhea have been
reported from the city in the past week.

A research scholar on the Indian economy from Argentina and an
American man were on the way to Manali from Chandigarh when they
stopped to have food at a dhaba in Ropar on Friday night, 1 Jul 2011.
Soon after dinner, they started feeling nauseous, followed by
vomiting. When their condition did not improve even after a visit to a
local RMP doctor, they were brought to the civil hospital. The
American was being kept in an emergency ward suffering from
dehydration following diarrhea.

Two residents of Ropar were also admitted to the emergency ward on
Sat 2 Jul 2011. According to reports, over 46 patients were found
affected by diarrhea and other gastrointestinal ailments during the
last 7 days. The outbreak has reportedly been triggered by poor
quality water supplied to the residents. A local resident, said:
"People here are deprived of fresh drinking water despite being
located on the banks of the Satluj river."

Ropar district health officer Dr Balbir Singh said: "We have already
instructed MC authorities in Ropar to take preventive measures and
have also set up 2 committees under deputy commissioner and civil
surgeon, Ropar to combat the epidemic." However, there were no reports
of any awareness campaign or preventive measures like providing
chlorine tablets or ORS solution to residents in affected areas,
sources said.

